cs.CV, cs.MM, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.IR 

This paper deals with the problem of multi-face tracking in unconstrained videos using convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to learn discriminative, video-specific face representations. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also involves unsupervised representation adaptation, which falls under the category of unsupervised learning, making cs.MM (Multimedia) another likely category. The paper also involves optimizing the embedding space using a triplet loss function, which falls under the category of metric learning, making cs.LG (Learning) another likely category. The paper also involves using contextual constraints to generate training samples, which falls under the category of knowledge representation and reasoning, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another likely category. Finally, the paper involves analyzing the contribution of each component, which falls under the category of information retrieval, making cs.IR (Information Retrieval) another likely category.
